column2: Guatemala
column3: and Honduras as the first concrete steps on the path to greater partnership and collaboration in the region laid out by President Biden
column4: ” Secretary of State Antony Blinken announced Saturday.  The agreements with El Salvador
column6: and Honduras required many migrants who showed up at the U. S. –Mexico border to seek asylum in one of those countries first.  The deals with El Salvador and Honduras were never formally enacted
column7: and the agreement with Guatemala has been effectively on hold since March due to the coronavirus pandemic.  “To be clear
column8: these actions do not mean that the U. S.  border is open.  While we are committed to expanding legal pathways for protection and opportunity here and in the region
column9: the United States is a country with borders and laws that must be enforced
column10: ” Blinken said in the statement.  “We are also committed to providing safe and orderly processing for all who arrive at our border
column11: but those who attempt to migrate irregularly are putting themselves and their families at risk on what can be a very dangerous journey
column12: ” he added.  President Biden is looking to undo other aspects of the Trump administration’s stringent immigration enforcement policies as well.  Last week
column13: the Biden administration announced the return of the so-called “catch and release” policy at the southern border

column2: trading links via Hong Kong’s exchange operator allowing mainland traders to buy domestic stocks will halt through Feb.  17 due to the Lunar New Year holiday.  The stock connect closure will slam the brakes on record levels of inflows that helped propel Hong Kong’s equities market to its best start to a year since 1985. Investors north of the border turned bargain hunters in late 2020 after valuations in some sectors onshore reached the highest in more than a decade.  Mainland investors net bought nearly $48 billion worth of Hong Kong stocks in the first five weeks of this year
column3: which is already more than half of 2020’s total.  They continued buying the city’s stocks on Monday

column2: but founder Masayoshi Son wiped out a significant chunk of those gains with his controversial trading in derivatives. The Vision Fund reported a 844. 1 billion yen ($8 billion) profit in the December quarter
column3: surpassing record numbers set just a quarter earlier.  A global rally in technology shares has boosted the value of SoftBank’s stakes in publicly traded firms like Uber Technologies Inc.  and paved the way for initial public offerings from the likes of DoorDash Inc. Those gains
column4: which had been widely expected
column5: were offset by fallout from Son’s decision last year to start dabbling in trading stocks and options.  SoftBank posted a 285. 3 billion yen derivatives loss in the period.  That led to an overall loss in the asset management arm of 113. 5 billion yen
column6: up from 85. 2 billion yen in the previous three-month period. “The Vision Fund’s stellar performance in the past few quarters continues to cover for the losses on options trading
column8: an analyst with Bloomberg Intelligence.  “SoftBank could argue those derivatives were for hedging purposes
column9: but Son’s venture into trading is definitely not looking good so far. ”In a presentation to investors after the results

column11: from Alibaba Group Holding Ltd.  and Yahoo! two decades ago
column12: to companies like Uber and DoorDash more recently.  Some 15 companies have gone public from the Vision Fund so far
column13: he said. “Since the Vision Fund launched
column14: the number of golden eggs is in accelerating mode
column16: pacing a stage in a white turtleneck sweater and grey jacket.  “We are finally in the harvesting stage. ”He said Vision Fund 1 and Vision Fund 2 have invested in a total of 131 companies.  In the case of DoorDash
column17: SoftBank invested about $680 million for a stake now worth about $9 billion
column19: while its $7. 7 billion investment in Uber is worth $11. 3 billion. The Tokyo-based company had a net income of 1. 17 trillion yen in the December period and did not release operating profit figures. column21: head of Asian research at United First Partners in Singapore.  “At some point the IPO fatigue sets in

column25: T-Mobile US Inc.  and SoftBank Corp.
column26: the Japan telecommunications unit.  SoftBank also announced a deal to sell its chip designer Arm Ltd.  to Nvidia Corp.  for $40 billion. SoftBank held a total of $22 billion of “highly liquid listed stocks” as of the end of quarter
column27: including a $7. 39 billion investment in Amazon. com Inc.
column28: $3. 28 billion in Facebook Inc.  and $1. 38 billion in Alphabet Inc.  The operation is managed by its asset management subsidiary SB Northstar
column29: where Son personally holds a 33% stake. The investments were accompanied by derivatives that amplified exposure
column30: but SoftBank has been winding down its options strategy amid a backlash from investors.  The fair value of SoftBank’s futures and options positions came to little over $1 billion at the end of December
column31: compared with $2. 7 billion the previous quarter.  Long call options on listed stocks have dwindled to $1. 68 billion from $4. 69 billion and short call options on listed stocks declined to $238 million from $1. 26 billion of value. Son said that the losses in the asset management arm have swung to a profit of about 100 billion yen since the end of last quarter.  But the operations remain in a “test-drive stage
column33: Son’s most stark investment success to date and SoftBank’s largest asset
column34: saw its shares plunge about 20% last quarter amid a Chinese government clampdown that scuttled the planned listing of its affiliate Ant Group Co.  Founder Jack Ma had all but vanished from public view
column35: prompting investor unease before he resurfaced last month. Son said he remained in touch with Ma
column36: without giving specific details of their communications.  He said Ma likes to draw and shares his drawings with Son via chat; the SoftBank chief also sketches but hasn’t shared any of his work.  Son also said he saw the increased antitrust scrutiny of Ma’s businesses in China as part of the country’s natural evolution. SoftBank’s own sale of Arm to Nvidia is still making its way through the approval process gauntlet.  The United Kingdom and European Union are both preparing to launch probes into the deal
column37: the Financial Times reported last week.  Son said he remained confident that it will receive a green light at the end. SoftBank has also joined the blank-check company frenzy with plans for several special purpose acquisition companies.  SVF Investment Corp.  raised $525 million last month to address sectors like mobile communications technology
column40: cloud technologies and software.  LDH Growth Corp I plans to raise as much as $200 million to target Latin American and Hispanic markets. SoftBank last week filed for two more SPACs
column41: seeking to raise another $630 million.  The new SoftBank vehicles
column43: will target the same diverse areas of technology as the first
column44: including mobile communications and artificial intelligence
column45: according to filings Friday with the Securities and Exchange Commission. “Consistently good performance by Vision Fund portfolio companies also helps the SPAC’s prospects because investors can extrapolate management expertise
column46: ” said Tang at United First Partners.  “It underlines their skill in deploying capital. ”SoftBank may see between 10 to 20 public listings a year from its portfolio of 164 startups across three different funds
column47: Son said.  A typical early-stage venture capital fund might see a third of its bets pay off
column48: but SoftBank’s portfolio of late-stage companies should do better than that
column49: he said.  Even WeWork has received SPAC interest
column50: he said. The billionaire struck a tone that was reminiscent of the days before the WeWork fiasco in late 2019.  He said the key to turning “white egg” investments into golden egg hits was “turbo-charging” startups with “overwhelming capital
column51: ” more ambitious goals and synergies with other portfolio companies. Son’s presentation then took a turn for the comical.  He flipped to an animated slide of a goose tagged with “AI revolution” text and a line of golden eggs marching out of its backside to Tchaikovsky’s Nutcracker. “Investment is a rhythm
column52: ” Son said.  “But please don’t look at this too seriously. ”(Updates with Son’s comments on Alibaba

column2: Sending Its Shares Soaring#https://finance.yahoo.com/news/palantir-teams-ibm-opening-path-103000378.html#https://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/pPs869gx3_MARAc7gO4C0w--~B/aD0xMzM0O3c9MjAwMDthcHBpZD15dGFjaHlvbg--/https://media.zenfs.com/en/bloomberg_markets_842/b72485e22588ce881bfb70ddb7700579#en#0.29600000000000004#finance.yahoo.com#(Bloomberg) -- Palantir Technologies Inc.  and International Business Machines Corp.  are uniting in a partnership that will dramatically expand the reach of Palantir’s sales force while making IBM’s own artificial-intelligence software easier for non-technical customers to use
column3: the companies plan to announce Monday. The global partnership is the largest of its kind for Palantir
column4: the maker of data-analysis software whose shares have more than quadrupled since its September debut on the New York Stock Exchange.  Palantir gains access to a sales team of more than 2
column6: up from its current 30.  Palantir’s stock rose as much as 12% in pre-market trading. The relationship is the payday for the project Palantir started more than a year ago to break its data integration and analysis software into smaller
column7: less pricey modules.  The Denver-based company mainly mainly sells to companies with revenue in excess of $500 million -- many of which already have relationships with IBM. Reselling Palantir’s software to augment the data and AI tools that IBM already offers and make them easier for more people to use was “a natural” fit
column8: said Rob Thomas
column9: IBM’s senior vice president of software
column10: cloud and data.  “We’re going to sell it to 180 countries and thousands of customers. ”Palantir’s software requires little to no coding
column11: enabling less technical employees to use it
column12: Thomas said.  To expand IBM’s cloud and AI business
column13: half the revenue will need to come through partnerships like the one struck with Palantir.  “That’s a pretty fundamental change for us
column14: ” he said. Expanded AccessWithout providing a time frame
column15: Thomas said he expects the partnership to help boost IBM’s customers using AI to 80% from its current 20%. Palantir Chief Operating Officer Shyam Sankar said the technical fit with IBM and its reach are part of his company’s long-term effort to finally ramp sales.  In addition to commercial customers
column16: government contracts have surged both in number and size during the pandemic. “This is the biggest [partnership[ we’ve announced -- expect more
column17: ” Sankar said.  He said he expects to triple Palantir’s direct-sales team to about 100 this year
column18: a significant hike for a company whose management once prided itself on not employing a single salesperson. Started with funding from PayPal co-founder Peter Thiel in 2003
column19: Palantir found early success with users at the U. S.  Central Intelligence Agency and went on to sign the Defense Department and Internal Revenue Service
column22: have used the software to locate roadside bombs and hunt tax cheats. Government ContractsMore recently the U. S.  Department of Health and Human Services and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention use Palantir’s software to help predict Covid-19 outbreaks
column23: distribute protective gear and allocate vaccines. While Palantir’s government contracts have grown -- sometimes amid privacy and surveillance concerns -- the company’s commercial business has been slower to evolve. Palantir last reported 132 total government and commercial clients
column24: a concentrated pool that includes BP Plc
column25: Merck KGaA and Airbus SE.  Early customers like American Express Co.  and Coca-Cola Co.  which experimented with low-cost Palantir software trials and later ditched them
column26: aren’t necessarily top of Palantir’s list now
column27: Sankar said. “We hope to win all this business back in the fullness of time
column29: adding there is no “pride list” of former customers it hopes to now re-engage. Palantir reports financial results for 2020 on Feb.  16.  A shareholder lockup expires three days later
column30: unleashing the remaining 80% of all shares that have not been eligible to trade.  Palantir shares rose $2 to $34. 05 on Feb.  5

column2: wrapping up the story in preparation for Endwalker.  The patch was previously announced at the Final Fantasy 14 showcase
column3: where CEO Yosuke Matsuda 'accidentally' let slip the patch's release date
column4: but with no additional details. Patch 5. 5
column6: will be split into two parts
column7: with the second half arriving in May.  Across the two parts
column8: patch 5. 5 will release new Main Scenario Quests tying up the Shadowbringers storyline and paving the way for Endbringer's release sometime this autumn.  The first half also brings the third chapter of the Nier crossover alliance raid
column9: YorHa: Dark Apocalypse.   New trials are also on the way.  The Cloud Deck Trial will introduce the Diamond Weapon
column10: available in both normal and extreme difficulties.  There's also a new Unreal Trial
column11: though we don't know which primal will be featured this time. The main story quests also bring the dungeon Paglth'an
column12: which can be completed in a party or using the Trust System.  And across the game
column13: all level 70 dungeons will be available in Explorer Mode—letting players dive into an enemy-less instance.  You'll be able to whip out your instrument of choice in Explorer Mode too
column14: thanks to the added ability to use performance actions.  You'll also be able to change instruments at any time while performing
column15: with a brand new mystery musical contraption on the way. The Sorrow or Werlyt and Save the Queen questlines are getting updates
column16: along with a new zone called Zadnor.  The relic weapons are also getting their final upgrades
column17: likely increasing the item level cap.  There'll be some general job adjustments
column19: and new custom deliveries too. This is all just for part one of Patch 5. 5
column21: with more story coming in part two later this year.  Check out the full update details here
column22: with more to come when the full patch notes arrive on April 13. #https://www.pcgamer.com/au/final-fantasy-14-55-update-detailed-will-pave-the-way-for-endwalkers-story/#Bo8uDLO3P

2021-02-06 11:30:58#local#Democrats Will Regret Their Move against Marjorie Taylor Greene#https://news.yahoo.com/democrats-regret-move-against-marjorie-113058115.html#https://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/xW12fSXluPB2OyNRy4zbwQ--~B/aD00NjQ7dz03OTY7YXBwaWQ9eXRhY2h5b24-/https://media.zenfs.com/en/the_national_review_738/0b2071b32c0e5576df0508f572842647#en#-0.4215#news.yahoo.com#At least Marjorie Taylor Greene won’t have to spend time sitting at the end of the dais during long committee hearings.  House Democrats voted to boot her from her committee assignments in an act that they will surely come to regret
column2: perhaps as soon as January 2023.  If the majority can keep members of the opposition party off of committees based on incendiary comments
column3: it’s not clear why the GOP ever let
column4: say
column5: Maxine Waters serve on any committees when it had control of the chamber
column6: or why it ever will again.  Kicking off Greene will come to be remembered as another inflection point in the steady unraveling of institutional norms on Capitol Hill.  That said
column7: we believe that Republicans should have taken matters into their own hands and denied Greene her committee assignments to draw a line against malicious lunacy in their own ranks.  That Democrats had a gun to his head with their threat to have a floor vote on Greene’s committee assignments probably made it more politically difficult for Minority Leader Kevin McCarthy to act on his own.  He did seek a deal with the Democrats to take her off the House Committee on Education and Labor and the Budget Committee and instead relegate her to the Small Business Committee.  When Democrats didn’t bite
column8: McCarthy again condemned her past comments and wrung an expression of regret from her in an internal GOP meeting earlier in the week that she repeated on the House floor on Thursday.  Her statement didn’t ring with sincerity
column9: but it was better than nothing
column10: even if she was immediately holding a combative press conference where she said
column11: “I’m fine with being kicked off committees because it’d be a waste of my time. ” We have
column13: not heard the last of her. #https://news.yahoo.com/democrats-regret-move-against-marjorie-113058115.html#RwBEmsorR

column1: 2021-02-06 15:55:00#local#Former CIA officer explains why Biden is right not to 'run the risk' of sending Trump intelligence briefings#https://news.yahoo.com/former-cia-officer-explains-why-155500145.html#https://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/_v045rXI4e0JPTdPZkQLQg--~B/aD01NjA7dz04NDA7YXBwaWQ9eXRhY2h5b24-/https://media.zenfs.com/en/the_week_574/62d5ddbd45af7ace5e955b5682cde3da#en#0.25#news.yahoo.com#"President Biden told CBS News' Norah O'Donnell he doesn't think former President Donald Trump should receive classified intelligence briefings
column2: questioning whether there's any upside to it and suggesting Trump's ""erratic behavior"" could lead to him eventually revealing sensitive information pertaining to national security.  It's not clear if Biden will officially cut off Trump's access
column3: but such a move would be unprecedented — traditionally
column4: former presidents can request and receive briefings.  David Priess
column5: who briefed former President George H. W.  Bush for many years after he left office
column6: told The Washington Post that ex-presidents continue to receive intelligence briefings because even though they're no longer in an official position of power
column7: they are considered representatives of the United States
column8: especially by foreign leaders
column9: for the rest of their lives.  He added that presidents also may turn to their predecessors for advice on international affairs.  That said
column10: Priess agrees with Biden that an exception could be made for Trump since ""there's no chance of Biden reaching out to Trump . . .  So why would Biden run the risk of Trump's disclosure of sensitive information by agreeing to such briefings?"" Journalist Yashar Ali did note that former presidents can also interact with other governments privately
column11: as former President Bill Clinton did when he traveled to North Korea in 2009 to secure the release of two journalists being held there.  Clinton
column13: notes was briefed even though it wasn't an official U. S.  government trip.  2.  For example
column14: when President Clinton when to North Korea to secure the release of two journalists who were being held by Kim Jong-Il
column15: he was given an intelligence briefing even though the trip was a private one and not an official US government trip.  — Yashar Ali (@yashar) February 6
column17: Trump wasn't exactly known for devouring his daily briefings while in office
column18: so it's not clear sending them now would offer the Biden administration much comfort
column19: either way.
